---
import MainLayout from '../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import { calculatorCanonical } from '../../lib/calculatorJsonLd';

const canonical = calculatorCanonical(Astro.site, Astro.url.pathname);

const softwareAppLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'SoftwareApplication',
  name: 'Income Tax Calculator India',
  applicationCategory: 'FinanceApplication',
  operatingSystem: 'Web Browser',
  offers: {
    '@type': 'Offer',
    price: '0',
    priceCurrency: 'INR',
  },
  description:
    'Free income tax calculator for India FY 2026-27 with Budget 2025 new regime slabs, ₹12 lakh rebate, and ₹75,000 standard deduction. Compare new vs old regime, enter deductions (80C, 80D, HRA). Browser-based, no data stored.',
  url: 'https://doitswift.com/calculator/income-tax/',
};

const faqPageLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is this official tax filing?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'No. This is an illustrative estimator for educational comparison only. It is not affiliated with the Income Tax Department and does not file returns. Official filing requires the government portal, Form 16 reconciliation, and verification of rebates and deductions for your assessment year. Always confirm figures with a chartered accountant or the department before you pay tax or file.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Which regime should I choose?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'The better regime depends on your income level and total deductions under Chapter VI-A, HRA, and home loan interest. The new regime offers lower slab rates but limits deductions; the old regime can win if your combined deductions are large enough. Use this calculator each year to compare side-by-side totals because budgets can change slabs and rebates. This tool gives a directional comparison only, not binding tax advice.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: "Why doesn't my tax match Form 16?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Employers compute TDS using payroll data, proof submissions, perquisites, and employer-specific policies that this page cannot replicate. Your Form 16 may include allowances, relief, and timing differences for HRA proofs and investment declarations. The calculator uses simplified slab math and your entered inputs only. For an exact match, reconcile with Form 16, AIS, and Form 26AS, and consult payroll or a tax professional if numbers diverge.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are cess and surcharge included?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'This calculator adds 4% health and education cess on the computed income tax for both regimes, which is how many people think about their final liability at common income levels. Surcharge on very high incomes is not modeled here, so if your taxable income crosses surcharge thresholds you should add surcharge manually or use detailed filing software. Cess applies on the tax amount after slabs, not on gross income, under both regimes.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is HRA calculated automatically?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'No. You must enter the HRA exemption amount you are eligible for based on metro rules, rent paid, and salary structure, or leave it at zero. Many taxpayers use an HRA calculator or employer worksheets first, then paste the exemption here for the old regime. If you do not pay rent or are not salaried under HRA rules, keep this at zero to avoid overstating old-regime benefits.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can NRIs use this calculator?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Non-resident Indians and other non-residents are taxed differently on income arising in India, and residential status affects exemptions and rebate eligibility. This tool assumes simplified resident individual rules for slab comparison. If you are an NRI or have split-year residency, adjust assumptions manually or seek professional advice because results may not reflect your actual filing position.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How do I calculate my income tax for FY 2026-27?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Enter your gross annual income in the calculator above, select your age group, choose the regime (new or old), and add any applicable deductions (80C, 80D, HRA for old regime). The calculator instantly shows your tax liability, effective tax rate, and taxable income. Compare both regimes to see which one saves more tax for your specific income and deduction profile. For official filing, verify with Form 16 and the Income Tax Department portal.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the tax-free income limit in India for FY 2026-27?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Under the new regime (Budget 2025 / FY 2026-27), income up to ₹12 lakh (after ₹75,000 standard deduction) is effectively tax-free due to the Section 87A rebate — meaning gross salary up to approximately ₹12.75 lakh results in zero tax. Under the old regime, the basic exemption is ₹2.5 lakh (below 60 years), ₹3 lakh (60-80), or ₹5 lakh (above 80), with rebate up to ₹5 lakh taxable income. The exact tax-free limit depends on which regime you choose and your deductions.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How much tax do I pay on ₹10 lakh salary?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Under the new regime (FY 2026-27): ₹10 lakh gross − ₹75,000 standard deduction = ₹9.25 lakh taxable. Since this is below the ₹12 lakh rebate threshold, tax is ₹0 under the new regime. Under the old regime with ₹2.5 lakh deductions (80C + 80D): taxable income ₹7 lakh, tax approximately ₹52,000 (before cess). At ₹10 lakh salary, the new regime wins decisively after Budget 2025 — the ₹12 lakh rebate effectively covers this income level. Enter your exact numbers above to compare.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can salaried employees choose between old and new regime every year?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Salaried employees (without business income) can switch between old and new regime every financial year. You don\'t need to inform your employer — you can claim whichever regime is more beneficial at the time of filing your return. Business/professional income taxpayers can switch only once in their lifetime. The new regime is the default since FY 2023-24; you must explicitly opt in to the old regime by filing Form 10-IEA.',
      },
    },
  ],
};

const breadcrumbLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://doitswift.com/' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Calculators', item: 'https://doitswift.com/calculator/' },
    {
      '@type': 'ListItem',
      position: 3,
      name: 'Income Tax Calculator',
      item: 'https://doitswift.com/calculator/income-tax/',
    },
  ],
};
---

<MainLayout
  title="Income Tax Calculator India FY 2026-27 | Budget 2025 Old vs New Regime | DoItSwift"
  description="Free income tax calculator for FY 2026-27 with Budget 2025 rates. Compare new vs old regime, ₹12 lakh rebate, ₹75K standard deduction. Enter salary and deductions to see which regime saves more tax."
  keywords="income tax calculator, income tax calculator india, tax calculator fy 2026-27, new vs old regime, income tax calculator online, salary tax calculator, 80c deduction calculator, old regime vs new regime, tax calculator india free, income tax slab 2026-27, budget 2025 tax calculator, income tax budget 2025, 12 lakh tax free, fy 2026-27 tax calculator, 75000 standard deduction"
  canonical={canonical}
>
  <script slot="head" is:inline src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@4.4.0/dist/chart.umd.min.js"></script>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(softwareAppLd)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqPageLd)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbLd)} />

  <nav class="breadcrumb container" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <a href="/">Home</a> › <a href="/calculator/">Calculators</a> › <span>Income Tax Calculator</span>
  </nav>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="badge">🧮 Free Calculator</div>
      <h1>Income Tax Calculator India — New vs Old Regime (FY 2026-27)</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">
        Calculate your Indian income tax for FY 2026-27 and compare the new tax regime with the old regime side by side. Enter your gross annual income, deductions under Section 80C, 80D, and HRA to see which regime saves you more tax. The calculator shows tax liability, effective tax rate, and taxable income under both regimes — helping you make an informed choice before filing. All calculations run in your browser; your salary and tax details are never sent to any server.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Updated for Budget 2025:</strong> The new tax regime now offers ₹12 lakh tax-free income (up from ₹7 lakh) thanks to the enhanced Section 87A rebate of ₹60,000. The standard deduction for salaried individuals increased to ₹75,000 (from ₹50,000). These changes make the new regime significantly more attractive for middle-income earners. The old regime rules remain unchanged — it still wins for those with substantial deductions (typically above ₹3.75-4 lakh).
      </p>
      <div class="trust">
        <span><span class="check">✓</span> No signup</span>
        <span><span class="check">✓</span> Instant results</span>
        <span><span class="check">✓</span> Works offline</span>
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: 12px; color: var(--text-muted); margin-top: 8px;">
        Slabs based on Union Budget 2025 announcements. Last updated: April 2026. This is an illustrative estimator only — verify with the Income Tax Department or a chartered accountant before filing.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <p class="disclaimer container">
    <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> Tax law changes frequently. This tool uses rounded slab math, a 4% health &amp; education cess on tax, standard deduction defaults (₹75,000 new / ₹50,000 old), and Budget 2025 rebate rules (new regime: no tax if taxable income ≤ ₹12 lakh). Surcharge on very high incomes is not modeled. Always validate against official Income Tax Department notifications for your assessment year.
  </p>

  <section class="calc-section">
    <div class="container calc-layout">
      <div class="calc-inputs">
        <h2 class="calc-heading">Inputs</h2>
        <div class="field">
          <label for="itGross">Gross annual income (₹)</label>
          <input type="number" id="itGross" min="0" step="1000" value="1200000" inputmode="numeric" aria-describedby="itGross-hint" />
          <p id="itGross-hint" class="field-hint">Salary, business, or combined — enter your total before Chapter VI-A (for comparison context).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="field">
          <label for="itAge">Age group</label>
          <select id="itAge" aria-label="Age group for basic exemption in old regime">
            <option value="below60" selected>Below 60</option>
            <option value="60to80">60 to 80</option>
            <option value="above80">Above 80</option>
          </select>
        </div>
        <div class="field">
          <label>Regime to preview</label>
          <div class="seg" role="radiogroup" aria-label="Tax regime">
            <label><input type="radio" name="itReg" value="new" checked /> New regime (default)</label>
            <label><input type="radio" name="itReg" value="old" /> Old regime</label>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="field">
          <label for="itStd">Standard deduction — salary, new regime (₹)</label>
          <input type="number" id="itStd" min="0" step="1000" value="75000" aria-describedby="itStd-hint" />
          <p id="itStd-hint" class="field-hint">Applied to new regime taxable income (default ₹75,000 for FY 2026-27 — verify for your year).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="field">
          <label for="itHRA">HRA exemption claimed — old regime (₹)</label>
          <input type="number" id="itHRA" min="0" step="1000" value="0" />
        </div>
        <div class="field">
          <label for="it80C">80C investments (₹, max ₹1.5L counted)</label>
          <input type="number" id="it80C" min="0" step="1000" value="150000" />
        </div>
        <div class="field">
          <label for="it80D">80D medical insurance (₹)</label>
          <input type="number" id="it80D" min="0" step="1000" value="25000" />
        </div>
        <div class="field">
          <label for="itOther">Other deductions — old regime (₹)</label>
          <input type="number" id="itOther" min="0" step="1000" value="0" />
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="calc-results" aria-live="polite">
        <h2 class="calc-heading">Results</h2>
        <div class="compare-grid">
          <div class="compare-card" id="boxNew">
            <h3>New regime</h3>
            <p class="big" id="itTaxNew">₹0</p>
            <p class="small">Tax + cess</p>
            <p class="line"><span>Taxable income</span><span id="itTiNew">₹0</span></p>
            <p class="line"><span>Effective rate</span><span id="itErNew">0%</span></p>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-card" id="boxOld">
            <h3>Old regime</h3>
            <p class="big" id="itTaxOld">₹0</p>
            <p class="small">Tax + cess</p>
            <p class="line"><span>Taxable income</span><span id="itTiOld">₹0</span></p>
            <p class="line"><span>Effective rate</span><span id="itErOld">0%</span></p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tips" id="itTips">
          <h4>Tax-saving ideas (generic)</h4>
          <ul id="itTipList"></ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="it-viz-section" aria-labelledby="it-viz-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 id="it-viz-heading" class="it-viz-heading">Visualize Your Tax Calculation</h2>
      <p class="it-viz-sub">See how each regime taxes your income, exactly when the old regime starts winning, and how deductions change your total tax.</p>

      <div class="it-winner-badge" id="itWinnerBadge" aria-live="polite">
        <span class="it-winner-icon">🏆</span>
        <div class="it-winner-text">
          <strong id="itWinnerLabel">—</strong>
          <span id="itWinnerSavings">Enter income to compare</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="it-chart-tabs" role="tablist" aria-label="Tax visualizations">
        <button type="button" class="it-chart-tab it-chart-tab--active" role="tab" aria-selected="true" aria-controls="itPanel0" id="itTab0" data-tab="0">Side-by-Side</button>
        <button type="button" class="it-chart-tab" role="tab" aria-selected="false" aria-controls="itPanel1" id="itTab1" data-tab="1" tabindex="-1">Slab Breakdown</button>
        <button type="button" class="it-chart-tab" role="tab" aria-selected="false" aria-controls="itPanel2" id="itTab2" data-tab="2" tabindex="-1">Break-Even</button>
        <button type="button" class="it-chart-tab" role="tab" aria-selected="false" aria-controls="itPanel3" id="itTab3" data-tab="3" tabindex="-1">Deduction Impact</button>
      </div>

      <div class="it-chart-panels">
        <div class="it-chart-panel it-chart-panel--active" role="tabpanel" id="itPanel0" aria-labelledby="itTab0" data-panel="0">
          <div class="it-chart-canvas-wrap">
            <canvas id="itVizCanvas0" aria-label="Side-by-side tax comparison between old and new regime"></canvas>
          </div>
          <p class="it-chart-callout" id="itChartCallout0" aria-live="polite"></p>
        </div>
        <div class="it-chart-panel" role="tabpanel" id="itPanel1" aria-labelledby="itTab1" data-panel="1" hidden>
          <div class="it-chart-canvas-wrap">
            <canvas id="itVizCanvas1" aria-label="Tax breakdown by slab showing how each portion of income is taxed"></canvas>
          </div>
          <p class="it-chart-callout" id="itChartCallout1" aria-live="polite"></p>
        </div>
        <div class="it-chart-panel" role="tabpanel" id="itPanel2" aria-labelledby="itTab2" data-panel="2" hidden>
          <div class="it-chart-canvas-wrap">
            <canvas id="itVizCanvas2" aria-label="Break-even chart showing at what income each regime is optimal"></canvas>
          </div>
          <p class="it-chart-callout" id="itChartCallout2" aria-live="polite"></p>
        </div>
        <div class="it-chart-panel" role="tabpanel" id="itPanel3" aria-labelledby="itTab3" data-panel="3" hidden>
          <div class="it-chart-canvas-wrap">
            <canvas id="itVizCanvas3" aria-label="How different deduction amounts affect old regime tax at your income"></canvas>
          </div>
          <p class="it-chart-callout" id="itChartCallout3" aria-live="polite"></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="edu">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">How Income Tax Works in India</h2>
      <p>
        India uses a <strong>progressive tax system</strong> — your income is taxed in slabs, with higher portions taxed at higher rates. You don't pay the highest rate on your entire income; each slab applies only to the income within that range. Under the new regime (post–Budget 2025 slabs for FY 2026-27), the first ₹4 lakh of taxable income is nil, and higher slices are taxed at 5% through 30% in steps — the Section 87A rebate can make tax zero up to ₹12 lakh taxable in many cases.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since FY 2020-21, taxpayers can choose between two systems: the <strong>new tax regime</strong> (lower rates, minimal deductions) and the <strong>old tax regime</strong> (higher rates but allows deductions like 80C, 80D, HRA, home loan interest). The new regime is the default since FY 2023-24, but you can opt for the old regime if it saves you more tax. This calculator helps you compare both instantly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="edu">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Income Tax Slabs FY 2026-27</h2>

      <h3>New regime tax slabs (Budget 2025 / FY 2026-27)</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap" style="overflow-x: auto; margin: 20px 0;">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Taxable income slab</th>
              <th>Tax rate</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Up to ₹4,00,000</td><td>Nil</td></tr>
            <tr><td>₹4,00,001 – ₹8,00,000</td><td>5%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>₹8,00,001 – ₹12,00,000</td><td>10%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>₹12,00,001 – ₹16,00,000</td><td>15%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>₹16,00,001 – ₹20,00,000</td><td>20%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>₹20,00,001 – ₹24,00,000</td><td>25%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Above ₹24,00,000</td><td>30%</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        <strong>Rebate under Section 87A (Budget 2025):</strong> If your taxable income after standard deduction is ₹12 lakh or below, tax is reduced to zero under the new regime. The rebate amount is up to ₹60,000 (increased from ₹25,000 in Budget 2025). Standard deduction for salaried individuals: ₹75,000 (increased from ₹50,000). This means gross salary up to approximately ₹12.75 lakh effectively results in zero tax under the new regime — a significant improvement for middle-income earners.
      </p>

      <h3>Old regime tax slabs</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap" style="overflow-x: auto; margin: 20px 0;">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Taxable income slab</th>
              <th>Below 60 years</th>
              <th>60-80 years</th>
              <th>Above 80 years</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Up to ₹2,50,000 / ₹3,00,000 / ₹5,00,000</td><td>Nil</td><td>Nil</td><td>Nil</td></tr>
            <tr><td>₹2,50,001 – ₹5,00,000</td><td>5%</td><td>5% (above ₹3L)</td><td>—</td></tr>
            <tr><td>₹5,00,001 – ₹10,00,000</td><td>20%</td><td>20%</td><td>20%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Above ₹10,00,000</td><td>30%</td><td>30%</td><td>30%</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        Under the old regime, taxable income is calculated after subtracting deductions: Section 80C (up to ₹1.5 lakh), Section 80D (medical insurance), HRA exemption, standard deduction, home loan interest (Section 24), and others. This is why the old regime can be better despite higher slab rates — if your total deductions exceed ₹3-4 lakh, the old regime often saves more tax.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="edu">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">New Regime vs Old Regime: Which Should You Choose?</h2>
      <div class="table-wrap" style="overflow-x: auto; margin: 20px 0;">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Factor</th>
              <th>New regime</th>
              <th>Old regime</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Tax rates</td>
              <td>Lower (5% to 30% across 7 income brackets)</td>
              <td>Higher (5% to 30% across 3 slabs)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Deductions allowed</td>
              <td>Minimal (standard deduction only)</td>
              <td>Extensive (80C, 80D, HRA, home loan, NPS, etc.)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Section 87A rebate</td>
              <td>Full rebate if taxable ≤ ₹12 lakh (up to ₹60,000 tax relief; Budget 2025)</td>
              <td>Full rebate if taxable ≤ ₹5 lakh</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Best for</td>
              <td>People with few deductions, simple salaries</td>
              <td>People with high deductions (rent, insurance, ELSS, home loan)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Complexity</td>
              <td>Simple — fewer inputs needed</td>
              <td>Complex — requires proof of investments and expenses</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Default since</td>
              <td>FY 2023-24 (must opt out to use old)</td>
              <td>Must explicitly opt in</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3>Quick decision rule</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>If your total deductions (80C + 80D + HRA + other) exceed ₹3.75 lakh,</strong> the old regime likely saves more tax. Below that threshold, the new regime's lower rates typically win. But this varies by income level — always compare both using the calculator above. At higher incomes (₹20 lakh+), even ₹2-3 lakh in deductions may not be enough to offset the new regime's lower rates.
      </p>
      <p>
        For a detailed analysis with Indian tax strategies, read our guide: <a href="/blog/old-vs-new-tax-regime/">Old vs New Tax Regime: Complete Comparison FY 2025-26</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="edu">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Key Tax Deductions Under the Old Regime</h2>
      <p>
        These deductions reduce your taxable income under the old regime. Enter them in the calculator above to see their impact on your tax liability:
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrap" style="overflow-x: auto; margin: 20px 0;">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Section</th>
              <th>Deduction for</th>
              <th>Maximum limit</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>80C</td><td>ELSS, PPF, EPF, NSC, life insurance, tuition fees, home loan principal</td><td>₹1,50,000</td></tr>
            <tr><td>80CCD(1B)</td><td>NPS contributions (additional)</td><td>₹50,000</td></tr>
            <tr><td>80D</td><td>Medical insurance premium (self + family)</td><td>₹25,000-₹1,00,000</td></tr>
            <tr><td>24(b)</td><td>Home loan interest (self-occupied property)</td><td>₹2,00,000</td></tr>
            <tr><td>10(13A)</td><td>HRA exemption (salaried, paying rent)</td><td>Based on formula</td></tr>
            <tr><td>80TTA</td><td>Savings account interest</td><td>₹10,000</td></tr>
            <tr><td>80E</td><td>Education loan interest</td><td>No upper limit</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Standard</td><td>Standard deduction (salaried)</td><td>₹75,000 (new) / ₹50,000 (old)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        A salaried individual maximizing 80C (₹1.5L), 80CCD(1B) (₹50K), 80D (₹25K), home loan interest (₹2L), and HRA (₹1.5L) can claim approximately ₹6.25 lakh in deductions — making the old regime significantly cheaper despite higher slab rates. Calculate your specific scenario using the inputs above.
      </p>
      <p>
        Use our <a href="/calculator/hra/">HRA Calculator</a> to compute your exact HRA exemption, and our <a href="/calculator/ppf/">PPF Calculator</a> to project your 80C investment returns.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="edu">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Worked Example: ₹15 Lakh Salary Under Both Regimes</h2>

      <h3>New regime calculation (Budget 2025 / FY 2026-27)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Gross income: ₹15,00,000</li>
        <li>Standard deduction: −₹75,000</li>
        <li>Taxable income: ₹14,25,000</li>
        <li>Tax: 5% on ₹4L (₹4L–₹8L) + 10% on ₹4L (₹8L–₹12L) + 15% on ₹2.25L (₹12L–₹14.25L) = ₹20,000 + ₹40,000 + ₹33,750 = ₹93,750</li>
        <li>Cess (4%): ₹3,750</li>
        <li><strong>Total tax: ₹97,500</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Old regime calculation (with moderate deductions)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Gross income: ₹15,00,000</li>
        <li>Standard deduction: −₹50,000</li>
        <li>80C (ELSS + EPF): −₹1,50,000</li>
        <li>80D (medical insurance): −₹25,000</li>
        <li>HRA exemption: −₹1,20,000</li>
        <li>Taxable income: ₹11,55,000</li>
        <li>Tax: Nil on ₹2.5L + 5% on ₹2.5L (₹12,500) + 20% on ₹5L (₹1,00,000) + 30% on ₹1.55L (₹46,500) = ₹1,59,000</li>
        <li>Cess (4%): ₹6,360</li>
        <li><strong>Total tax: ₹1,65,360</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Verdict for this example</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>New regime saves ₹67,860</strong> (₹1,65,360 − ₹97,500). With ₹3.45 lakh in old regime deductions, the new post–Budget 2025 regime still wins at ₹15 lakh income because lower slab rates plus the higher standard deduction (₹75,000) outweigh the old regime's Chapter VI-A benefits in this profile. The old regime would need substantially more deductions (e.g. higher HRA, home loan interest, NPS) to pull ahead. Try your exact numbers in the calculator above.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="edu">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Understanding Tax Concepts</h2>

      <h3>What is cess?</h3>
      <p>
        Health and Education Cess is a 4% surcharge applied on the total income tax amount (not on income). If your tax is ₹1,00,000, cess adds ₹4,000, making your total ₹1,04,000. Cess is non-deductible and applies under both regimes.
      </p>

      <h3>What is surcharge?</h3>
      <p>
        Surcharge is an additional tax on high incomes — 10% surcharge on income above ₹50 lakh, 15% above ₹1 crore, 25% above ₹2 crore. This calculator does not model surcharge — if your income exceeds ₹50 lakh, add surcharge manually or consult a CA. Surcharge rates may differ between regimes.
      </p>

      <h3>What is standard deduction?</h3>
      <p>
        For FY 2026-27, salaried individuals and pensioners typically get ₹75,000 in the <strong>new</strong> tax regime and ₹50,000 in the <strong>old</strong> regime (verify against official notifications for your exact case). It is subtracted from gross salary before tax slabs. No investment proof is required for this component — the calculator above follows these defaults.
      </p>

      <h3>How is CTC different from taxable income?</h3>
      <p>
        Your CTC (Cost to Company) includes employer PF contribution, gratuity, insurance, and other components that may not be taxable or may have separate rules. Taxable income starts from gross salary (CTC minus employer's PF, gratuity, and non-taxable allowances). Use our <a href="/calculator/salary/">Salary Calculator</a> to convert CTC to in-hand salary, then use this tax calculator for tax estimation.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

