  <section class="faq">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Frequently asked questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is this official tax filing?</h3>
          <p>
            No. This is an illustrative estimator for educational comparison only. It is not affiliated with the Income Tax Department and does not file returns. Official filing requires the government portal, Form 16 reconciliation, and verification of rebates and deductions for your assessment year. Always confirm figures with a chartered accountant or the department before you pay tax or file.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Which regime should I choose?</h3>
          <p>
            The better regime depends on your income level and total deductions under Chapter VI-A, HRA, and home loan interest. The new regime offers lower slab rates but limits deductions; the old regime can win if your combined deductions are large enough. Use this calculator each year to compare side-by-side totals because budgets can change slabs and rebates. This tool gives a directional comparison only, not binding tax advice.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Why doesn't my tax match Form 16?</h3>
          <p>
            Employers compute TDS using payroll data, proof submissions, perquisites, and employer-specific policies that this page cannot replicate. Your Form 16 may include allowances, relief, and timing differences for HRA proofs and investment declarations. The calculator uses simplified slab math and your entered inputs only. For an exact match, reconcile with Form 16, AIS, and Form 26AS, and consult payroll or a tax professional if numbers diverge.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Are cess and surcharge included?</h3>
          <p>
            This calculator adds 4% health and education cess on the computed income tax for both regimes, which is how many people think about their final liability at common income levels. Surcharge on very high incomes is not modeled here, so if your taxable income crosses surcharge thresholds you should add surcharge manually or use detailed filing software. Cess applies on the tax amount after slabs, not on gross income, under both regimes.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is HRA calculated automatically?</h3>
          <p>
            No. You must enter the HRA exemption amount you are eligible for based on metro rules, rent paid, and salary structure, or leave it at zero. Many taxpayers use an HRA calculator or employer worksheets first, then paste the exemption here for the old regime. If you do not pay rent or are not salaried under HRA rules, keep this at zero to avoid overstating old-regime benefits.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Can NRIs use this calculator?</h3>
          <p>
            Non-resident Indians and other non-residents are taxed differently on income arising in India, and residential status affects exemptions and rebate eligibility. This tool assumes simplified resident individual rules for slab comparison. If you are an NRI or have split-year residency, adjust assumptions manually or seek professional advice because results may not reflect your actual filing position.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How do I calculate my income tax for FY 2026-27?</h3>
          <p>
            Enter your gross annual income in the calculator above, select your age group, choose the regime (new or old), and add any applicable deductions (80C, 80D, HRA for old regime). The calculator instantly shows your tax liability, effective tax rate, and taxable income. Compare both regimes to see which one saves more tax for your specific income and deduction profile. For official filing, verify with Form 16 and the Income Tax Department portal.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is the tax-free income limit in India for FY 2026-27?</h3>
          <p>
            Under the new regime (Budget 2025 / FY 2026-27), income up to ₹12 lakh (after ₹75,000 standard deduction) is effectively tax-free due to the Section 87A rebate — meaning gross salary up to approximately ₹12.75 lakh results in zero tax. Under the old regime, the basic exemption is ₹2.5 lakh (below 60 years), ₹3 lakh (60-80), or ₹5 lakh (above 80), with rebate up to ₹5 lakh taxable income. The exact tax-free limit depends on which regime you choose and your deductions.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How much tax do I pay on ₹10 lakh salary?</h3>
          <p>
            Under the new regime (FY 2026-27): ₹10 lakh gross − ₹75,000 standard deduction = ₹9.25 lakh taxable. Since this is below the ₹12 lakh rebate threshold, tax is ₹0 under the new regime. Under the old regime with ₹2.5 lakh deductions (80C + 80D): taxable income ₹7 lakh, tax approximately ₹52,000 (before cess). At ₹10 lakh salary, the new regime wins decisively after Budget 2025 — the ₹12 lakh rebate effectively covers this income level. Enter your exact numbers above to compare.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Can salaried employees choose between old and new regime every year?</h3>
          <p>
            Salaried employees (without business income) can switch between old and new regime every financial year. You don't need to inform your employer — you can claim whichever regime is more beneficial at the time of filing your return. Business/professional income taxpayers can switch only once in their lifetime. The new regime is the default since FY 2023-24; you must explicitly opt in to the old regime by filing Form 10-IEA.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

